lli and J.S. Mill, the book analyses how modern technology has influenced democracy.Among the issues discussed in the book are why people vote and what determines their decisions, what prompts citizen involvement in riots and demonstrations, whether spin doctors and designer politics pose a threat to democracy and the influence of mass media on our political behaviour.More than merely providing an overview, the book also presents original analyses of timely issues such as referendums and the consequences of postal voting.An essential book for students of politics, history and media studies, this study puts the debate about democracy into perspective and offers a solid grounding for future discussions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aPolitical participationvCase studies. 0aPolitical participation. 0aPublic opinion. 0aReferendumvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aJ.S. Mill.  aMachiavelli.  aPlato.  acitizen participation.  ademocracy.  ademonstrations.  amodern technology.  apolitical behaviour.  ariots.1 aQvortrup, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779230340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792303/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles